🔥 What is CI/CD Pipeline?

👉 CI (Continuous Integration)
→ Automatically build & test code when developers push changes

👉 CD (Continuous Deployment/Delivery)
→ Automatically deploy the application to server

🧠 Simple Meaning
“CI/CD pipeline automates the process from writing code → testing → deploying → making it live”

🚀 Complete CI/CD Flow (Step-by-Step)
Developer → Git → CI Tool → Build → Test → Docker → Push → Deploy → Live
🧩 Step 1: Developer Pushes Code

👉 Developer writes code and pushes to GitHub

git add .
git commit -m "Added new API"
git push origin main

➡ This triggers the pipeline automatically

🧩 Step 2: CI Tool Triggers Pipeline

👉 Tools:
Jenkins
GitHub Actions
GitLab CI

➡ Pipeline starts when code is pushed

🧩 Step 3: Build Phase

👉 Compile the code
mvn clean install

➡ Output:
.jar file created
user-service.jar

🧩 Step 4: Run Tests
👉 Automatically runs:
Unit tests (JUnit)
Integration tests

➡ If tests fail:
❌ Pipeline stops
➡ If pass:
✅ Move to next step

🧩 Step 5: Code Quality Check (Optional but real-time)
👉 Tools:
SonarQube

➡ Checks:
Code quality
Bugs
Security issues

🧩 Step 6: Build Docker Image
👉 Convert app into container
docker build -t user-service .

🧩 Step 7: Push to Docker Registry
docker push myrepo/user-service

👉 Stored in:
Docker Hub
AWS ECR

🧩 Step 8: CD – Deployment to Kubernetes
👉 Pipeline deploys app automatically
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

➡ Kubernetes:

Pulls latest image
Creates new pods

🧩 Step 9: Rolling Update (Zero Downtime)
👉 Old version replaced gradually

Old Pods ↓
New Pods ↑

➡ Users don’t see downtime

🧩 Step 10: Application is Live

👉 Now accessible:

https://api.myapp.com/users
