🔥 Where API Gateway Fits in Flow

After Kubernetes:
Client → API Gateway → Kubernetes Services → Pods → Response

👉 API Gateway acts as single entry point

🧠 Why API Gateway is Needed --> without gaterway client need to all apis, urls 

Without Gateway:
Client → user-service
Client → order-service
Client → payment-service

❌ Client must know all services

With Gateway:
Client → API Gateway → All services

✅ Clean, secure, centralized

🚀 How API Gateway is Set Up (Step-by-Step)
🧩 Step 1: Create API Gateway Service

👉 Usually built using:

Spring Cloud Gateway (Java projects)
NGINX / Kong (production setups)
Example: Spring Cloud Gateway Dependency
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-gateway</artifactId>
</dependency>
🧩 Step 2: Configure Routing

👉 You define which request goes to which service

Example (application.yml):
spring:
  cloud:
    gateway:
      routes:
        - id: user-service
          uri: http://user-service:8080
          predicates:
            - Path=/users/**

        - id: order-service
          uri: http://order-service:8080
          predicates:
            - Path=/orders/**

👉 Meaning:

/api/users → user-service  
/api/orders → order-service
🧩 Step 3: Deploy API Gateway to Kubernetes

👉 Just like other microservices:

Build JAR
Create Docker image
Push to registry
Deploy in Kubernetes
api-gateway
 └── Pod (running gateway)
🧩 Step 4: Expose Gateway to Outside World

👉 This is the MOST IMPORTANT STEP

Kubernetes exposes gateway using:

🔹 Option 1: LoadBalancer (Common in cloud)
kind: Service
type: LoadBalancer

➡ Gives public IP

🔹 Option 2: Ingress (Advanced & preferred)

👉 Acts like smart router

Internet → Ingress → API Gateway → Services
🧩 Step 5: Service Discovery (Optional but important)
👉 If using Eureka:

uri: lb://USER-SERVICE

➡ Gateway dynamically finds service

🧩 Step 6: Add Cross-Cutting Features

👉 API Gateway also handles:
🔐 Security
JWT validation
🚦 Rate Limiting
Prevent too many requests
📊 Logging
Track requests
🔄 Routing & Filtering
🧠 Real-Time Example Flow
Client Request:
https://api.myapp.com/orders

↓
API Gateway

↓ (route based on path)
order-service
↓
Kubernetes Service
↓
Pod
↓
Response → Gateway → Client

🎯 Interview Answer (Perfect)
“After deploying microservices in Kubernetes, we set up an API Gateway as a separate service. 
It is configured with routing rules to forward client requests to appropriate services.
The gateway is deployed in Kubernetes and exposed externally using LoadBalancer or Ingress. 
It also handles cross-cutting concerns like security, logging, and rate limiting.”

